<Base title="Quick Start" description="From zero to a scaffolded substrate project in under five minutes.">
  <h1>Quick Start</h1>
  <p>From zero to a scaffolded substrate project in under five minutes.</p>

  <h2>1. Scaffold your project</h2>
  <p>From your repo root:</p>
  <pre><code>npx @op4z/substrate@latest init --bridge claude</code></pre>
  <p>This creates:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>substrate.config.json</code> at the repo root.</li>
    <li><code>auto/</code> with the seven canonical subdirectories
      (<code>commands</code>, <code>instructions</code>, <code>scripts</code>,
      <code>config</code>, <code>standards</code>, <code>audits</code>,
      <code>docs</code>).</li>
    <li><code>auto/.substrate-manifest.json</code> tracking every scaffolded file.</li>
    <li><code>.claude/commands/substrate.md</code> for the Claude Code slash command.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>2. Add an audit</h2>
  <pre><code>npx substrate add audit backend</code></pre>
  <p>
    Drops <code>auto/instructions/main/audit-backend.md</code> into your repo.
    Edit it — it's yours now. Substrate reads from your copy at runtime.
  </p>

  <h2>3. Run the audit</h2>
  <pre><code>npx substrate audit --type backend</code></pre>

  <h2>4. Run via Claude Code</h2>
  <p>In Claude Code, type:</p>
  <pre><code>/substrate audit --type backend</code></pre>
  <p>
    The slash command dispatches to the same CLI, loading the audit's
    instruction file into Claude's context so it can produce the
    AI-guided report.
  </p>

  <h2>5. Upgrade as substrate evolves</h2>
  <pre><code>npx substrate upgrade --check       # See what's drifted
npx substrate upgrade --apply       # Walk modified entries interactively</code></pre>
  <p>
    For modified files, substrate shows you a three-way diff (original
    template → your current copy → new template) and lets you choose
    <em>keep / take-new / merge / eject</em>.
  </p>

